  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages (1970s-1980s)\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international guidelines by Basel Committee\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- United Nations Convention against Illicit Drugs (1988)\n- Patriot Act (2001) expanded anti-money laundering (AML) provisions\n\n3. Regulatory Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Advanced technology for transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional banking\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Complex cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n- Integration of artificial intelligence in detection\n\n6. Global Standardization\n- Consistent regulatory frameworks\n- Mutual evaluation processes\n- Blacklisting of high-risk jurisdictions\n\nThese developments reflect growing complexity in financial crimes and technological advancements.",
